am, Wiltshire, England":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Stafford, Staffordshire, England":"Stafford, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Mountjoy, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1261–1342":"1261–1342","1261–1318":"1261–1318","1281–1350":"1281–1350","1293–1334":"1293–1334","–Male":"Deceased","about 1293":"about 1293","1350":"1350","1261":"1261","1293":"1293","1281":"1281","1290":"1290","Abt 1262":"about 1262","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1334":"1334","1453":"1453","Abt 1275":"about 1275","1342":"1342","1318":"1318","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Worcestershire, England":"Worcestershire, England","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Worcester, Worcestershire, England":"Worcester, Worcestershire, England","Stafford, Staffordshire, England":"Stafford, Staffordshire, England","England":"England","Mountjoy, Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mountjoy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon and Gloucestershire; of Norman origin): habitational name, ultimately from <i>Montjoie</i>, a crusaders’ name derived from that of the mountain in Palestine from which the first view of Jerusalem was obtained. The name was adopted for several places in western Europe (notably Montjoie-Saint-Martin in Manche), and this, or the original, could have given rise to the English surname."],"variants":[{"name":"Montjoy","meanings":["Altered form of English   Mountjoy  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":29,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":54,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":67,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":76,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret of Mountjoy was born in 1261, in Worcestershire, England. She married Sir Ralph de Mountjoy about 1275, in Worcestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1342, in England, at the age of 81."},"et":{"1261–1342":"1261–1342","1261–1318":"1261–1318","1281–1350":"1281–1350","1293–1334":"1293–1334","–Male":"Surnud","about 1293":"umbes 1293","1350":"1350","1261":"1261","1